ence in the context of an individual’s culturally constituted existence. In addition to examining the extent to which local understandings of pain’s characteristics are personalized by individual sufferers, the book sheds important new light on how pain is implicated in the fashioning of particular Yapese understandings of ethical subjectivity and right action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMedical anthropologyzMicronesia (Federated States)zYap. 0aPainxTreatmentzMicronesia (Federated States)zYap. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aacute pain.  aanthropology.  abelief systems.  achronic pain.  acultural anthropology.  acultural experiences.  aculture of pain.  aethical subjectivity.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  aexpressing pain.  afederated states of micronesia.  ahuman condition.  ahuman experience.  ahuman struggles.  aisland of yap.  aknowledge.  alocal customs.  amorality.  apain sufferers.  apain.  apersonal accounts.  apersonal experiences.  asensory experiences.  asuffering.  avalues.  avicissitudes.  awaqab.  ayapese culture.  ayapese life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026057340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094593740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945937/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY